Thank you @markap14 for the review and suggestion. Definitely, it make lot of sense to not write to a flowfile when HandleHttpResponse is not terminated and if the previous content is needed. Also, it will add additional overhead of overwriting when HandleHttpResponse is terminated like you mentioned. Instead, we can send status message to `response.getOutputStream()` when `Http Status Message` property is set otherwise follow existing step of exporting flowfile content to response.getOutputStream()

``` 
// if statusMessage property is set
if (!StringUtils.isBlank(statusMessage)) {
   try(OutputStream out = response.getOutputStream();) {
        out.write(statusMessage.getBytes());
   }
} else {
   session.export(flowfile, response.getOutputStream());
}
```   

This will also be beneficial to send different response back when failed and further continue to process the failure such as sending email or writing the failed content somewhere. It will also avoid using Processors like ReplaceText (for writing failure response message) and ExtractText for example ( to restore back our previous content if we want to continue further processing if HandleHttpResponse is not terminated) specifically on failures. 

**Example**

Existing approach
` HandleHttpRequest -> ... ExtractText -> ReplaceText --> HandleHttpResponse -> (restore back content for further processing from ExtractText)`

When Status Message property is set
 ` HandleHttpRequest -> ....... --> HandleHttpResponse (set status message) -> (continue rest of the processing)`

 Please suggest if this looks. I can make above changes. Thanks again.

@naddym yes that is exactly what I had in mind.
One other interesting note to consider: Your check above:
`if (!StringUtils.isBlank(statusMessage)) {` may not be exactly correct, because the status message may be an empty string, and if I'm not mistaken that is perfectly valid. And in fact, I think for something like a 204 it MUST be empty.
So we'd want to check:
```
try(OutputStream out = response.getOutputStream()) {
    if (statusMessage == null) {
         session.export(flowfile, response.getOutputStream());
    } else {
        out.write(statusMessage.getBytes());
    }
}
```
And make sure that the validator allows for an empty string (i.e., use Validator.VALID)
